{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"11940f79-edd3-43f9-8e92-739fcaaf1f84","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n**1. Expensive property function — file I/O during evaluation** (line 13, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`ReadAllText` forces synchronous disk I/O every time the project is evaluated (IDE load, design-time builds, restore, etc.). Property functions that hit the filesystem are one of the most common eval-time perf killers.\n\n**2. Overly broad glob pattern** (line 9, `.csproj`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nA recursive `**\\*.*` wildcard forces MSBuild to walk the entire directory tree on every evaluation. As the repo grows, this cost grows linearly. Prefer a scoped directory or specific extensions.\n\n**3. Deeply chained `<Import>` files** (`level1 → level2 → level3`)\nEach import is resolved and parsed sequentially during evaluation. Three levels here is mild, but the pattern invites growth. Flattening or consolidating props reduces evaluation passes and file-open overhead.\n\n---\n\n### Recommendations\n\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| `File::ReadAllText` | Move file reading to a target (runs at build time, not eval time), or use a `ReadLinesFromFile` task. |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Narrow to specific extensions (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or a specific subdirectory. |\n| Nested imports | Consolidate into fewer files or flatten the chain to reduce import depth. |\n\nThe biggest win is removing the property function; the glob is the second-most impactful issue for larger trees.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2cdf170b-4238-48d1-aa62-650155cbef4b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a clear picture of the project. Let me analyze the MSBuild evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":475,"requestId":"1C38:222DF7:A6421C:C3EF95:69F40156"},"id":"ba85f5a